709254f-b.title: Manhattan : 6th Avenue  - Watts Street.
709254f-b.text:
(11)
Sixth Avenue, west side, north from and including WWatts Street,
along the line of and including the former Clark Street, which has
been absorbed by Sixth Avenue. No. 4o Watts Street, which used to
be two doors from the N.W. corner of Sullivan and Watts Streets, is
now practically at the N.W. corner of Sixth Avenue.
1932.
J. Clarence Davies Collection, Museum of the City of New York.
Negative No. 305.
CREDIT LINE IMPERATIVE ON ALL REPRODUCTIONS.
(2)
The same during the extension of Sixth Ave. Note the political banners
upon the fire escapes of No. 46. They depict the Democratic presidential
candidates, Alfred E. Smith and William T. Robinson.

Sixth Ave. (Extension), east side, south from and including Wat ts

724293f-a.title: Manhattan: Watts Street - 6th Avenue
724293f-a.text:
53 to 61 Watts Street, south side, between Sixth Ave. Extension and
Varick Street, showing three 5-story tenements (Nos. 57-61) under
demolition. These adjoin the 10-story structure (extreme right) at the
S.E. corner of this street and Varick Street. The two 3-story buildings
areJframe construction with brick fronts and are east of the latter.
October 18, 1937.
P. L. Sperr.
NO REPRODUCTIONS.
